282
00:17:13,280 --> 00:17:19,340
And of course, this is all especially difficult because this is the first virtual world con.

283
00:17:19,340 --> 00:17:24,560
And so there are going to be extra difficulties and problems associated with that.

284
00:17:24,900 --> 00:17:31,580
But it sounds like coming this letter, although not public, are some suggestions for ways in which these problems could be mitigated.

285
00:17:31,580 --> 00:17:38,900
Yes. And the tweeted question was posted by Alistair Stewart, who is a nominee for, sorry, who is a finalist for Best Fan Writer.

286
00:17:38,900 --> 00:17:46,220
And people may know him as well for being a host on the Escape Pod family of podcasts.

287
00:17:46,220 --> 00:17:48,580
My thoughts on this are...

288
00:17:48,580 --> 00:17:51,960
Good job, Mark, protecting there, John. Protecting the Hugo finalist, Mark.

289
00:17:51,960 --> 00:17:54,000
Yeah. Well, you know...

290
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:54,720
You can cut that bit, sorry.

291
00:17:54,720 --> 00:17:56,200
I just got...

292
00:17:56,200 --> 00:17:57,820
Because I was like, Alistair's not called Mark.

293
00:17:57,820 --> 00:18:09,800
Which is like, Mark Plummer has done a number on my ability to accurately talk around my role on the Mark Protection Committee.

294
00:18:09,800 --> 00:18:13,120
So, the...

295
00:18:13,120 --> 00:18:14,700
I have thoughts about this.

296
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:17,640
I am a Hugo finalist, as has been previously mentioned.

297
00:18:17,640 --> 00:18:22,820
I am not on the ConZealand programme because I am not attending ConZealand.

298
00:18:22,820 --> 00:18:26,940
I did get a programme participant survey, I think.

299
00:18:26,940 --> 00:18:30,040
But I didn't fill it in because I'm not going.

300
00:18:31,040 --> 00:18:37,060
I, in general, can see the point that the signatories of the letter are making.

301
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:46,540
But I think my thoughts on this are neatly encapsulated by something that listener Emily January said to me and Liz in another place and another time.

302
00:18:47,040 --> 00:18:54,600
Which is that I understand that I understand that representation is very important.

303
00:18:54,600 --> 00:18:57,840
So, the Worldcon to feel like they're being invited in if they get nominated for Hugos.

304
00:18:57,840 --> 00:19:01,520
And I can see why having Hugo finalists on the programme is really important.

305
00:19:01,520 --> 00:19:08,880
But, however, I think that there is also an argument that the Worldcon is by and for the Worldcon membership.

306
00:19:09,340 --> 00:19:19,240
And so, if someone is not a member of the Worldcon, it is not necessarily the case that they should be invited to be on the programme if they haven't signed up.

307
00:19:19,240 --> 00:19:31,020
So, I think there is, in some ways, a clash here between Worldcon as a thing that is put on by its members and the expectation that you will be invited even if you are not a member.

308
00:19:31,680 --> 00:19:39,840
And I think that is a complex discussion that kind of runs up a little bit about the Worldcon style of having members instead of tickets.

309
00:19:39,840 --> 00:19:52,140
And I wonder whether conventions that are more ticket-based might be skewing this conversation slightly in a way that is a little bit antithetical to how Worldcons have traditionally worked.

310
00:19:52,140 --> 00:19:59,120
And I do think that there is another element here, which Emily pointed out,

311
00:19:59,320 --> 00:20:04,140
which is that she has chatted to newer convention attendees at Easter Cons,

312
00:20:04,140 --> 00:20:06,480
who she has said, oh, you'd be great on programme.

313
00:20:06,480 --> 00:20:08,540
And they've said, I can't be on programme, I'm not an author.

314
00:20:08,540 --> 00:20:16,580
And I think this idea that to be on programme, you need to be a professional or need to be recognised in some way is dangerous,

315
00:20:16,580 --> 00:20:21,420
because I think, in general, programming is about putting interesting people on panels.

316
00:20:21,800 --> 00:20:31,040
But having said all of that, obviously, people who get nominated for Hugos and become Hugo finalists are perhaps interesting people who it would be good to have on panels.

317
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:33,760
So maybe those aren't antithetical concepts.

318
00:20:33,760 --> 00:20:39,780
So my thoughts on this are all very wishy-washy and nuanced, which is unhelpful for polemic.

319
00:20:39,780 --> 00:20:41,980
Alison, be forthright.

320
00:20:42,240 --> 00:20:44,460
I agree with everything that John said.

321
00:20:44,460 --> 00:20:49,620
So I think some of the wishy-washy stuff there is fine.

322
00:20:49,620 --> 00:20:57,740
I also note that people are kind of like, I got offered programme, but it wasn't the exact programme item I wanted to do,

323
00:20:57,740 --> 00:21:00,780
to which I would say that's a thing you can suck up.

324
00:21:00,940 --> 00:21:07,100
But I also note that they say the programme is not diverse enough and it doesn't feature,

325
00:21:07,100 --> 00:21:16,100
it doesn't have enough diversity in its range and scope, and it doesn't have enough diversity of participants.

326
00:21:16,100 --> 00:21:21,860
And that, I think, Con Zealand, if it had got its act together four or five weeks earlier,

327
00:21:21,860 --> 00:21:24,000
would have done well to have a think about.

328
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,440
It's now clearly too late for them to do that.

329
00:21:27,620 --> 00:21:31,060
Some of the Australian and New Zealand fans I have spoken to have said,

330
00:21:31,060 --> 00:21:34,940
you need to remember as well, this is a New Zealand Worldcon,

331
00:21:34,940 --> 00:21:38,280
and they are, and I think 100% correctly,

332
00:21:38,280 --> 00:21:44,260
foregrounding Australian and New Zealand creators and fans in the programme.

333
00:21:44,260 --> 00:21:48,640
And that is absolutely the right thing for them to be doing.

334
00:21:48,640 --> 00:21:54,860
Part of what you do when you have a local Worldcon is showcase what you are doing,

335
00:21:54,860 --> 00:21:59,240
both professionally and fancially in science fiction, for the world.

336
00:21:59,240 --> 00:22:05,000
And I think that's inevitably going to lead to some voices,

337
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:11,760
particularly voices from American participants,

338
00:22:11,760 --> 00:22:14,960
not getting as much attention as they often do.

339
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:17,160
I have no idea where Alice Stewart comes from.

340
00:22:17,160 --> 00:22:18,300
He's British.

341
00:22:18,300 --> 00:22:22,060
I should say the spreadsheet is a private suggestion of spreadsheets,

342
00:22:22,060 --> 00:22:24,580
which I think is correct, is the correct way to do it.

343
00:22:24,580 --> 00:22:25,820
There's an open letter,

344
00:22:25,820 --> 00:22:29,800
and then they have privately sent a set of helpful suggestions to the programme team,

345
00:22:29,800 --> 00:22:31,620
which I think is absolutely the right way to do it.

346
00:22:31,620 --> 00:22:33,820
Well, it's a good way of doing it,

347
00:22:33,820 --> 00:22:36,160
because it doesn't turn it into a giant mudslinging flight,

348
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:39,280
but it also implements concrete suggestions.

349
00:22:39,280 --> 00:22:42,040
I think there's a few aspects of this.

350
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:47,080
One is, I think it is normal, or at least it's been normal when I've been involved,

351
00:22:47,080 --> 00:22:52,740
to get in touch with all the Hugo finalists who you know are attending to say,

352
00:22:52,740 --> 00:22:54,720
hi, would you like to do some programme?

353
00:22:54,720 --> 00:22:58,420
But part of this is about the Hugo finalists who are not attending,

354
00:22:58,420 --> 00:23:01,400
who do not have a comped membership.

355
00:23:02,060 --> 00:23:03,740
But part of the issue is that usually,

356
00:23:03,740 --> 00:23:08,860
because the expense of attending a Worldcon is way more than just the membership,

357
00:23:08,860 --> 00:23:12,280
it ends up being that even if you gave free memberships to every Hugo,

358
00:23:12,280 --> 00:23:15,960
every Hugo finalist, many of them still wouldn't be able to attend.

359
00:23:15,960 --> 00:23:22,320
I feel like if they comped membership for every Hugo finalist who was not already an attending membership,

360
00:23:22,320 --> 00:23:28,820
they would have a much bigger problem on their hands than the problems that they currently find themselves.

361
00:23:29,140 --> 00:23:33,920
Because all the Hugo finalists who had maybe, at some considerable expense themselves,

362
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:35,920
because it's not cheap, joined the convention.

363
00:23:35,920 --> 00:23:41,380
This is another argument for why you should be Eurocon and charge 10 euros for your membership.

364
00:23:41,380 --> 00:23:44,000
I still haven't joined yet, but I must do this.

365
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:46,720
Or UK Games Expo and charge absolutely nothing.

366
00:23:46,720 --> 00:23:50,960
I mean, I have had discussions about whether we should just be giving comped Worldcon memberships

367
00:23:50,960 --> 00:23:54,880
to all Hugo finalists, like, as a matter of policy,

368
00:23:54,880 --> 00:23:57,320
and, you know, refunding the ones who already had memberships.

369
00:23:57,420 --> 00:24:01,980
But it does, in any normal Worldcon, end up being quite a lot of your members.

370
00:24:01,980 --> 00:24:04,460
There are quite a lot of Hugo finalists as well.

371
00:24:04,460 --> 00:24:06,840
And they're, in fact, increasing numbers of Hugo finalists,

372
00:24:06,840 --> 00:24:14,420
because we have a lot of multi-editor podcasts and magazines, which is great.

373
00:24:14,420 --> 00:24:16,380
But it does just increase those numbers again.

374
00:24:16,540 --> 00:24:21,360
So I think we worked out that you'd have to comp, like, a substantial fraction of the membership,

375
00:24:21,360 --> 00:24:22,980
which would be an issue.

376
00:24:22,980 --> 00:24:28,040
But with this being a virtual Worldcon, that issue is partly sidestepped,

377
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:29,880
because you don't have a membership cap.

378
00:24:29,880 --> 00:24:31,960
You don't have the physical facilities.

379
00:24:31,960 --> 00:24:33,680
Your costs are not as high.

380
00:24:33,680 --> 00:24:38,100
So in this case, I think they could consider comping every Hugo finalist.

381
00:24:38,100 --> 00:24:43,100
So my thought on this is effectively something that Alison knows I have strong feelings on,

382
00:24:43,100 --> 00:24:49,440
which is I generally think this problem is being caused by the fact that the membership is far, far too expensive.

383
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:56,940
And the fact that we have seen, like, zero other science fiction conventions charge in excess of about $30,

384
00:24:56,940 --> 00:25:02,620
and this one costs somewhere in the region of five times that, is tricky.

385
00:25:02,620 --> 00:25:07,060
And I sympathize for the ConZealand Committee, and there must be reasons they're doing that.

386
00:25:07,060 --> 00:25:10,400
And I suspect those reasons are things they can't easily get out of.

387
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:20,060
But honestly, I think the whole thing is being caused by the fact that this is a hell of a value proposition for a virtual convention.

388
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:24,620
And I think it's difficult, because you're quite right that in general,

389
00:25:24,620 --> 00:25:31,900
comping Hugo finalist memberships would not enable them to attend the convention anyway,

390
00:25:31,900 --> 00:25:33,300
so there's not much point in doing it.

391
00:25:33,300 --> 00:25:38,680
But this year, it would be necessary to do that for most of them to attend.

392
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:43,160
And also, it's the one year that doing it would mean they could participate.

393
00:25:43,160 --> 00:25:47,720
So it changes the conversation a lot compared to normal Worldcons

394
00:25:47,720 --> 00:25:50,740
and other virtual conventions running alongside the Worldcon.

395
00:25:50,740 --> 00:25:52,380
I have two thoughts.

396
00:25:52,380 --> 00:25:57,700
The first is that one of the things that has been a little less nice about my guff trip

397
00:25:57,700 --> 00:25:59,360
has actually been a bit sad,

398
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:02,460
is that I keep having conversations with people where I say,

399
00:26:02,460 --> 00:26:03,980
and are you going to ConZealand?

400
00:26:03,980 --> 00:26:05,500
And people are saying,

401
00:26:05,500 --> 00:26:08,320
no, it's far too expensive.

402
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:09,480
I can't do it.

403
00:26:09,480 --> 00:26:13,180
And I've kind of got used to those conversations in Britain.

404
00:26:13,180 --> 00:26:20,860
But I have been quite sad and surprised by the extent to which I'm having them in Australia.

405
00:26:20,860 --> 00:26:23,000
And I think that's...

406
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:26,600
It's really interesting, because I had assumed the reason I was talking to a lot of British people

407
00:26:26,600 --> 00:26:29,540
who weren't going was because those people were not planning to go anyway.

408
00:26:29,540 --> 00:26:32,620
But if people from Australia and New Zealand are not planning to go,

409
00:26:32,840 --> 00:26:37,300
that says something quite significant, I think, about ConZealand's pricing structure,

410
00:26:37,300 --> 00:26:41,620
because I would have expected anyone who had been planning to go to the Worldcon

411
00:26:41,620 --> 00:26:43,660
to have been attending the virtual Worldcon.

412
00:26:43,660 --> 00:26:47,100
The people who already had attending memberships have kept them.

413
00:26:47,100 --> 00:26:48,000
They did.

414
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:56,380
Their kind of partial refund system has worked in terms of keeping their attending members for the most part.

415
00:26:56,380 --> 00:27:00,360
I don't think a lot of people who had attending memberships have scrapped them.

416
00:27:00,360 --> 00:27:06,600
But people who were hoping to go or have not picked up the virtual membership,

417
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:10,880
just the same way that they haven't in the UK as well.

418
00:27:10,880 --> 00:27:12,840
So I thought that was a bit sad.

419
00:27:13,340 --> 00:27:18,140
My second point was, having said that they clearly cannot routinely comp membership

420
00:27:18,140 --> 00:27:21,460
for every Hugo finalist, because that enormous number of Hugo finalists,

421
00:27:21,460 --> 00:27:26,940
I think they might manage to comp membership for every Hugo finalist

422
00:27:26,940 --> 00:27:31,440
who is not already an attending member and is from a marginalised group

423
00:27:31,440 --> 00:27:35,540
and suggests that they may have financial problems managing the cost of membership.

424
00:27:35,540 --> 00:27:37,840
Because I don't suppose that's actually going to be that many people.

425
00:27:37,840 --> 00:27:40,240
So that would have been a thing that they could do.

426
00:27:40,680 --> 00:27:43,280
And certainly, I don't know if this is true of Worldcons,

427
00:27:43,280 --> 00:27:48,940
but in the UK, we have an honourable tradition of having an unwaged membership level,

428
00:27:48,940 --> 00:27:51,580
which is available to you if you feel you need it,

429
00:27:51,580 --> 00:27:57,520
rather than making it sort of a thing where you have to be able to prove that you need it,

430
00:27:57,520 --> 00:28:00,980
which I think is in general a good model for doing that sort of thing.

431
00:28:01,480 --> 00:28:03,760
It's not a lot cheaper, but it is something.

432
00:28:03,760 --> 00:28:06,040
You could have the same system here where you say,

433
00:28:06,040 --> 00:28:10,880
look, if you are from a marginalised background and, you know,

434
00:28:10,880 --> 00:28:14,200
you would like a comp membership, we're not going to ask questions.

435
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:15,980
You know, we're not going to ask you to prove anything about it.

436
00:28:15,980 --> 00:28:16,540
We just will.

437
00:28:16,540 --> 00:28:20,520
So my other thought is that having only very briefly looked at the Conzealum programme,

438
00:28:20,520 --> 00:28:23,540
because I'm not going, it's got a lot of programme items,

439
00:28:23,680 --> 00:28:27,180
but I think it's still got quite a lot fewer than at a regular Worldcom,

440
00:28:27,180 --> 00:28:28,460
which I think makes sense.

441
00:28:28,460 --> 00:28:32,180
I don't think you want like 15 to 20 programme items running simultaneously.

442
00:28:32,180 --> 00:28:34,120
I think you probably want five to 10,

443
00:28:34,120 --> 00:28:36,680
but it means there are many fewer spots on the programme.

444
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:40,740
And I also wonder if they're having an issue of time zones,

445
00:28:40,740 --> 00:28:44,500
because one of the things that has become increasingly difficult

446
00:28:44,500 --> 00:28:47,180
when programming Worldcoms is trying to do the scheduling.

447
00:28:47,180 --> 00:28:52,840
It is like a, you know, multi-week nightmarish jigsaw puzzle.

448
00:28:52,840 --> 00:28:55,300
And that is with everyone in the same time zone,

449
00:28:55,300 --> 00:28:58,440
to try and get everyone on items with the right people

450
00:28:58,440 --> 00:29:01,600
and to find a time when all those people are available at the Con.

451
00:29:01,600 --> 00:29:04,980
And, you know, there will always be commitments people have.

452
00:29:04,980 --> 00:29:06,760
There will be people who don't like doing late evening panels,

453
00:29:06,760 --> 00:29:08,500
people who don't like doing morning panels and so on.

454
00:29:08,500 --> 00:29:10,020
And sometimes you do go, okay,

455
00:29:10,020 --> 00:29:12,540
this would be the ideal set of people for this panel,

456
00:29:12,540 --> 00:29:15,440
but there is no time slot that actually works.

457
00:29:15,440 --> 00:29:16,500
And so I have to change it up.

458
00:29:16,820 --> 00:29:19,260
And I wonder if time zones are causing even more of a problem,

459
00:29:19,260 --> 00:29:22,280
because if your ideal panel would have someone who's in Europe,

460
00:29:22,280 --> 00:29:25,120
someone who's in New Zealand and someone who's in the USA,

461
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:27,480
that's going to be very difficult to do.

462
00:29:27,480 --> 00:29:30,900
So I wonder if sometimes the way that they have solved

463
00:29:30,900 --> 00:29:34,720
problematic scheduling issues is to drop people

464
00:29:34,720 --> 00:29:36,020
who would otherwise be good on the panels

465
00:29:36,020 --> 00:29:39,560
and replace them with someone who just has more availability.

466
00:29:39,560 --> 00:29:43,480
I think I'm sure that the time zone scheduling

467
00:29:43,480 --> 00:29:44,720
has been an absolute nightmare.

468
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:46,420
And they can't, you know,

469
00:29:46,420 --> 00:29:48,920
I basically told them I would be on Australia and New Zealand time,

470
00:29:48,920 --> 00:29:51,140
but I've been given at least one panel on European time.

471
00:29:51,140 --> 00:29:54,460
And luckily it's at 10 o'clock at night,

472
00:29:54,460 --> 00:29:55,480
New Zealand time,

473
00:29:55,480 --> 00:29:56,940
because I'm kind of a late bird,

474
00:29:56,940 --> 00:29:58,220
will probably be okay.

475
00:29:58,220 --> 00:30:00,600
But it's quite a serious panel.

476
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:02,760
And normally at a British convention,

477
00:30:02,760 --> 00:30:05,100
I go on panels at 10 o'clock at night

478
00:30:05,100 --> 00:30:07,660
and they're all the kind of lighter hearted ones.

479
00:30:07,660 --> 00:30:08,980
So I don't know whether,

480
00:30:08,980 --> 00:30:10,500
how it's going to work in practice.

481
00:30:10,900 --> 00:30:12,580
One other thing I wanted to point out.

482
00:30:12,580 --> 00:30:17,460
So I was complaining about the cost of Con Zealand

483
00:30:17,460 --> 00:30:19,560
relative to other online conventions.

484
00:30:19,560 --> 00:30:22,020
And we mentioned that the Eurocon this year is 10 euros.

485
00:30:22,020 --> 00:30:24,940
I will say that there's the opposite,

486
00:30:24,940 --> 00:30:27,320
the opposite problem occurs to me,

487
00:30:27,320 --> 00:30:27,980
which is,

488
00:30:27,980 --> 00:30:30,760
is this partly because we as a community

489
00:30:30,760 --> 00:30:34,160
are not valuing our time as volunteers enough?

490
00:30:34,160 --> 00:30:37,580
And we actually should be charging more than 10 euros

491
00:30:37,580 --> 00:30:40,960
for what is probably really quite a lot of work.

492
00:30:40,960 --> 00:30:43,500
Is this something where Con Zealand

493
00:30:43,500 --> 00:30:45,440
are actually charging an appropriate amount of money

494
00:30:45,440 --> 00:30:46,980
for what it is they're planning to put on?

495
00:30:46,980 --> 00:30:50,460
And other conventions are so severely undervaluing

496
00:30:50,460 --> 00:30:54,580
their offerings that Con Zealand

497
00:30:54,580 --> 00:30:55,820
are suffering as a result.

498
00:30:55,820 --> 00:30:57,860
But we always undervalue our volunteer labour

499
00:30:57,860 --> 00:30:59,920
because we essentially put thousands of hours

500
00:30:59,920 --> 00:31:01,240
of volunteer labour in for no money.

501
00:31:01,400 --> 00:31:03,780
all the actual costs that you pay for Worldcon

502
00:31:03,780 --> 00:31:05,980
is going to the physical facilities

503
00:31:05,980 --> 00:31:09,060
and the paid staff of the venue.

504
00:31:09,060 --> 00:31:10,820
It's not going to anyone organising it.

505
00:31:10,820 --> 00:31:13,240
So it would be a completely different model

506
00:31:13,240 --> 00:31:15,980
if you started charging for virtual conventions

507
00:31:15,980 --> 00:31:19,000
because of the volunteer time you're putting into them.

508
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:20,940
I can understand charging in order to make sure

509
00:31:20,940 --> 00:31:22,060
you have, you know,

510
00:31:22,060 --> 00:31:25,280
a sufficiently good Zoom and Discord licence and so on.

511
00:31:25,360 --> 00:31:27,460
But if we're going to actually start saying,

512
00:31:27,460 --> 00:31:31,140
OK, and then we will somehow compensate people

513
00:31:31,140 --> 00:31:32,600
for the volunteer labour you've put in,

514
00:31:32,600 --> 00:31:34,900
then you are, one, changing the whole model

515
00:31:34,900 --> 00:31:36,560
and two, you're probably going to get yourself

516
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:37,820
into a very sticky situation

517
00:31:37,820 --> 00:31:39,660
because you're then employing people.

518
00:31:39,660 --> 00:31:40,620
That's a good point.

519
00:31:40,620 --> 00:31:42,320
I'm not sure if that was what you were proposing.

520
00:31:42,320 --> 00:31:43,480
Not as such.

521
00:31:43,480 --> 00:31:45,320
I guess I wasn't trying to argue

522
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:47,340
that they should pay volunteers as if they're employees,

523
00:31:47,340 --> 00:31:49,100
but I do wonder to what extent

524
00:31:49,100 --> 00:31:51,660
Con Zealand are using more services

525
00:31:51,660 --> 00:31:53,320
which do this sort of thing professionally

526
00:31:53,320 --> 00:31:56,660
because they partnered with the Fantasy.network

527
00:31:56,660 --> 00:31:58,320
and people like that.

528
00:31:58,320 --> 00:32:01,060
And I do wonder whether part of this disconnect

529
00:32:01,060 --> 00:32:02,020
is coming from,

530
00:32:02,020 --> 00:32:04,160
this is an appropriate amount of money

531
00:32:04,160 --> 00:32:05,360
to spend for this sort of event,

532
00:32:05,360 --> 00:32:08,540
but most other places are much more relying

533
00:32:08,540 --> 00:32:10,240
on volunteer labour to make it work.

534
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:13,460
OK, so we always rely on volunteer labour

535
00:32:13,460 --> 00:32:14,420
to make things work.

536
00:32:14,420 --> 00:32:16,760
I think Con Zealand decided,

537
00:32:16,760 --> 00:32:18,440
possibly correctly,

538
00:32:18,440 --> 00:32:20,440
possibly not so correctly,

539
00:32:20,760 --> 00:32:23,560
that they didn't have the skills within fandom

540
00:32:23,560 --> 00:32:25,560
to do everything that they wanted to do

541
00:32:25,560 --> 00:32:28,120
and so would need to use paid labour

542
00:32:28,120 --> 00:32:32,780
for something that would normally be volunteer labour.

543
00:32:32,780 --> 00:32:36,080
But in fact, their primary things are,

544
00:32:36,080 --> 00:32:36,580
you know,

545
00:32:36,580 --> 00:32:37,620
we're going to send you an email

546
00:32:37,620 --> 00:32:38,760
with your Zoom links in it.

547
00:32:38,760 --> 00:32:40,000
We're going to be on Discord.

548
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:42,540
I mean, this doesn't seem to be that much different

549
00:32:42,540 --> 00:32:43,760
from what Balticon did

550
00:32:43,760 --> 00:32:46,300
and Balticon managed with its existing volunteer knowledge.

551
00:32:46,300 --> 00:32:48,060
You know, we've built up some knowledge

552
00:32:48,060 --> 00:32:49,500
in this area in the last few months.

553
00:32:49,500 --> 00:32:52,520
I mean, I don't want to criticise Con Zealand

554
00:32:52,520 --> 00:32:56,220
too strongly for a decision that they took under pressure.

555
00:32:56,220 --> 00:32:58,740
I feel like they're doing their best job they can

556
00:32:58,740 --> 00:33:00,260
to run a good convention

557
00:33:00,260 --> 00:33:02,420
under extremely difficult circumstances.

558
00:33:02,420 --> 00:33:04,320
But I feel like,

559
00:33:04,320 --> 00:33:06,260
considering that we are all volunteers

560
00:33:06,260 --> 00:33:08,300
and we are generally happy to,

561
00:33:08,300 --> 00:33:10,060
you know, we muddle along

562
00:33:10,060 --> 00:33:13,480
in slightly good, less good hotels than we might

563
00:33:13,480 --> 00:33:15,460
and slightly less good circumstances

564
00:33:15,460 --> 00:33:17,140
than we might generally at conventions

565
00:33:17,140 --> 00:33:21,840
because we're actually after the volunteer feeling of it

566
00:33:21,840 --> 00:33:24,580
and the relatively cheap thing.

567
00:33:24,580 --> 00:33:27,680
I think that the models that we see going forward

568
00:33:27,680 --> 00:33:29,020
will be cheaper than Con Zealand.

569
00:33:29,020 --> 00:33:30,780
They may not be as cheap as Eurocon.

570
00:33:30,780 --> 00:33:32,060
We'll have to see how that goes.

571
00:33:32,060 --> 00:33:34,640
A lot of the professional conferences

572
00:33:34,640 --> 00:33:37,800
I might consider going to have gone online

573
00:33:37,800 --> 00:33:40,040
and their virtual registration rates

574
00:33:40,040 --> 00:33:41,220
are usually somewhere between

575
00:33:41,220 --> 00:33:43,820
sort of maybe 20 to 60 pounds.

576
00:33:43,820 --> 00:33:46,440
So they are a cut above Eurocon,

577
00:33:46,440 --> 00:33:48,420
but they're not as much as Con Zealand.

578
00:33:49,420 --> 00:33:51,260
And so this actually neatly dovetails

579
00:33:51,260 --> 00:33:52,660
into the next point I was going to make,

580
00:33:52,660 --> 00:33:54,200
which is, is the other mistake,

581
00:33:54,200 --> 00:33:56,460
potentially, that Con Zealand has made

582
00:33:56,460 --> 00:33:59,440
not relying on sponsorships?

583
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:01,560
Because, like, the UK Games Expo

584
00:34:01,560 --> 00:34:02,860
is doing everything for free,

585
00:34:02,860 --> 00:34:03,920
but they're being sponsored

586
00:34:03,920 --> 00:34:06,480
by some of the largest companies in the industry

587
00:34:06,480 --> 00:34:08,280
and a large part of the money

588
00:34:08,280 --> 00:34:10,160
they'll be spending to make their convention go

589
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:11,860
is being provided by those companies.

590
00:34:11,860 --> 00:34:14,020
Now, Worldcons have not traditionally

591
00:34:14,020 --> 00:34:15,940
relied on sponsorships

592
00:34:15,940 --> 00:34:18,300
and there are contentious discussions

593
00:34:18,300 --> 00:34:19,460
to have about that.

594
00:34:19,460 --> 00:34:20,340
And I have been present

595
00:34:20,340 --> 00:34:21,200
for some of those discussions,

596
00:34:21,200 --> 00:34:22,500
even though I am a baby fan.

597
00:34:22,500 --> 00:34:25,780
Worldcon has an interesting sponsorship history,

598
00:34:25,780 --> 00:34:29,800
which I think we should take another time.

599
00:34:29,800 --> 00:34:31,280
But it is fair to say

600
00:34:31,280 --> 00:34:34,940
that in general, but not always,

601
00:34:34,940 --> 00:34:36,700
Worldcons have happily taken

602
00:34:36,700 --> 00:34:38,560
some money from publishers

603
00:34:38,560 --> 00:34:40,340
and Eastercons, for that matter.

604
00:34:40,340 --> 00:34:41,900
But it's not normally,

605
00:34:41,900 --> 00:34:44,140
there's not normally the amount of money

606
00:34:44,140 --> 00:34:45,700
flushing around in the industry.

607
00:34:45,700 --> 00:34:47,340
that there can be

608
00:34:47,340 --> 00:34:49,380
if we were taking money

609
00:34:49,380 --> 00:34:52,560
from television or movie studios, say.

610
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:55,900
So publishing is more marginal generally.

611
00:34:55,900 --> 00:34:58,340
However, I remember having a chat

612
00:34:58,340 --> 00:34:59,780
with Patrick Nielsen Hayden of Tor

613
00:34:59,780 --> 00:35:03,100
where the Toronto Worldcon

614
00:35:03,100 --> 00:35:04,300
was called TorCon,

615
00:35:04,300 --> 00:35:06,000
TorCon 2 or TorCon 3.

616
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:07,880
And Tor Books basically went,

617
00:35:07,880 --> 00:35:09,140
yeah, no, we'll spot,

618
00:35:09,140 --> 00:35:11,120
I see you have this range

619
00:35:11,120 --> 00:35:12,240
of possible sponsorships,

620
00:35:12,240 --> 00:35:13,680
sponsorship things.

621
00:35:13,680 --> 00:35:15,360
Can we have the biggest one, please?

622
00:35:15,360 --> 00:35:16,800
Which I think is quite cute.

623
00:35:16,800 --> 00:35:19,340
They weren't called TorCon because of that.

624
00:35:19,340 --> 00:35:21,600
But in general, there are issues,

625
00:35:21,600 --> 00:35:23,300
there are some sponsoring issues.

626
00:35:23,300 --> 00:35:27,220
We are not very good at acquiring sponsorship

627
00:35:27,220 --> 00:35:30,360
and then finding appropriate ways to use it

628
00:35:30,360 --> 00:35:33,340
that don't worry our membership.

629
00:35:33,700 --> 00:35:37,420
I think another good example of recent sponsorship is

630
00:35:37,420 --> 00:35:39,400
San Jose's, sorry,

631
00:35:39,400 --> 00:35:40,900
Worldcon 76,

632
00:35:40,900 --> 00:35:42,920
San Jose 2018.

633
00:35:42,920 --> 00:35:44,980
They had their Hugo ceremony

634
00:35:44,980 --> 00:35:46,280
and it was sponsored by Google

635
00:35:46,280 --> 00:35:47,780
and they gave a free Google Home

636
00:35:47,780 --> 00:35:51,260
to all of the Hugo reception attendees that year.

637
00:35:52,380 --> 00:35:56,860
And because Google does not have an obvious conflict of interest

638
00:35:56,860 --> 00:35:59,180
with any of the kind of Hugo finalists,

639
00:35:59,180 --> 00:36:01,380
that went entirely unremarked upon

640
00:36:01,380 --> 00:36:03,260
and I think was generally a very good idea.

641
00:36:03,260 --> 00:36:05,140
So maybe that's the other thing,

642
00:36:05,140 --> 00:36:07,360
which is science fiction fandom in theory

643
00:36:07,360 --> 00:36:11,360
leans towards friendliness to technology

644
00:36:11,360 --> 00:36:13,240
and to other such things.

645
00:36:13,240 --> 00:36:16,420
So perhaps going to a technology sector

646
00:36:16,420 --> 00:36:18,460
which is increasingly flush

647
00:36:18,460 --> 00:36:20,480
or maybe even going to somewhere like Weta,

648
00:36:20,480 --> 00:36:23,660
who are obviously a homegrown New Zealand institution

649
00:36:23,660 --> 00:36:25,560
but aren't necessarily explicitly competing

650
00:36:25,560 --> 00:36:27,160
for any of the Hugo categories.

651
00:36:27,160 --> 00:36:28,940
There might have been options,

652
00:36:28,940 --> 00:36:31,020
but it's very easy to quarterback these decisions

653
00:36:31,020 --> 00:36:32,340
when you're not the one making them

654
00:36:32,340 --> 00:36:33,320
under incredible pressure.

655
00:36:33,320 --> 00:36:35,880
And I do think Alison's point about that is valid.

656
00:36:35,880 --> 00:36:38,040
I realised that one of the other things I do

657
00:36:38,040 --> 00:36:39,580
is the MIT puzzle hunt

658
00:36:39,580 --> 00:36:45,080
and the MIT puzzle hunt is entirely paid for, really,

659
00:36:45,080 --> 00:36:47,340
by sponsorship from tech companies.

660
00:36:47,340 --> 00:36:49,020
And when these tech companies talk about

661
00:36:49,020 --> 00:36:50,900
why they sponsor the MIT puzzle hunt,

662
00:36:50,900 --> 00:36:54,880
it's like there is no better place to recruit in the world

663
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:57,620
than by the sort of people who like spending three days

664
00:36:57,620 --> 00:37:00,620
of their weekend solving very hard puzzles for fun.

665
00:37:00,620 --> 00:37:03,040
Is it too soon to say

666
00:37:03,040 --> 00:37:05,220
Eastercon needs to think about going virtual?

